# AMAMA collector output format

This document defines the **on-disk artifacts produced by the collector
stage** and the contract Agent 1 / the grep script consume.

Target: Volatility 3 (vol3) for memory-image triage.

---

## 1. Decision: two files, two formats

| File                       | Format            | Consumer       | Why                                    |
|----------------------------|-------------------|----------------|----------------------------------------|
| `collector_summary.txt`    | structured text   | Agent 1 (LLM)  | minimal tokens, max LLM readability    |
| `collector_deep.json`      | JSON              | grep script    | exact lookups by PID / path            |

### Why plain text for the summary (not JSON)

Token cost of the same information, rough cl100k_base estimates:

| Encoding for one flagged process               | tokens |
|------------------------------------------------|-------:|
| JSON object (keys + quotes + braces)           | ~50    |
| YAML                                           | ~35    |
| **Structured text (this design)**              | ~22    |

For a typical case with ~5-20 flagged processes, 5-10 persistence keys, and
a process tree of ~30 visible nodes, the text summary lands at **~1-3 KB
(~700-1500 tokens)**. JSON for the same data would be 4-8 KB and add a lot
of noise (`"pid":`, commas, brackets) that the LLM has to skip past.

LLMs are excellent at reading markdown-ish structured text -- they were
trained on millions of incident reports, blog posts, and pastebin dumps in
exactly this shape. JSON is great when the LLM has to *emit* structured
output (function calling), not when it has to *consume* a triage report.

### Why JSON for the deep index

The grep script is deterministic Python -- it needs O(1) lookups by PID
and by path, no parsing tricks. JSON is the obvious choice and stays
machine-readable for debugging.

